First rollout sample: ["<｜begin▁of▁sentence｜><｜User｜>Stan and Ollie are playing a game starting with two integers 320 and 500. Stan goes first.\n\nOn each turn, a player may subtract any **positive multiple** of one integer from the other, as long as the result is **non-negative**. The player who makes one of the numbers become **zero** wins the game.\n\nIf both players always play optimally, who will win — Stan or Ollie?\n\n**Output Format:** Your final answer should be a single word: either `Stan` or `Ollie` (do **NOT** include quotes or backticks), indicating the winner.<｜Assistant｜><think>\nOkay, so I need to determine whether Stan or Ollie will win this game starting from 320 and 500, with Stan going first.\n\nLet me read the game again. It's a two-player game where Stan starts. On each turn, a player subtracts any positive multiple from one integer to make the other play with smaller numbers, and who can make one of them zero wins.\n\nThis sounds similar to the Euclidean algorithm or the concept of the greatest common divisor (GCD). Maybe it's related?\n\nLet me recall: In such subtraction games involving GCD, typically if subtractable steps can reduce towards GCD.\n\nFirst, let's note the initial numbers: 320 and 500.\n\nI should find the GCD of 320 and 500 to see some property.\n\nCalculating GCD of 320 and 500:\n\nUsing Euclidean algorithm:\n\n500 divided by 320 gives remainder: 500 - 1*320 = 180.\n\nGCD(320, 500) = GCD(320, 180).\n\nNow, GCD(320, 180):\n\n320 ÷ 180 = 1 with remainder 140.\n\nGCD(180,140):\n\n180 ÷140 = 1 rem 40\n\nGCD(140,40):\n\n140 ÷40 = 3 rem 20\n\nGCD(40,20):\n\n40 ÷20 = 2 rem 0. So GCD is 20.\n\nSo the GCD of 320 and 500 is 20.\n\nHmm, now in games like this, sometimes being able to divide into multiples of GCD determines the winner? Or perhaps think in terms of modulo.\n\nWait the standard approach in games like the Euclid game is deciding based on whether it's a winning or losing position based on the subtraction options. Maybe it's