rs when divided by GCD (which is 20) become:\n\n320 /20=16; 500/20=25.\n\nSo game equivalent is two numbers 16 and 25.\n\nWhat starting with GCD 1 may affect who can win.\n\nWait perhaps with the starting numbers a and b, the starting position to a subtraction game of GCD is it a winning or losing position for the first player. If the starting pair is such that (a1, b1)=(16,25) with b1 > a1.\n\nCompute Grundy numbers? Maybe not.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the game where you subtract multiples is similar to Nim with Grundy number based on Grundy(n). Alternatively, since it's a subtraction game akin to the Euclid, someone winning based on winning positions.\n\nIn the standard subtraction game where players subtract any multiple of one from the larger, the Grundy number is known if the numbers are multiples?\n\nWait perhaps better to model the game using modulo relation.\n\nThe game is similar to Euclid's game where players subtract multiples until one hits zero.\n\nSince the GCD is 20, perhaps the key is whether the larger number is a multiple of the smaller.\n\nWait, b=500 and a=320, 500 divided by GCD is 25 vs 16.\n\nWait 500/20=25 and 320/20=16 so we have (16, 25). Now, in this scaled game, 16 and25.\n\nWe can use the idea that the first player can subtract multiples:\n\n25 -1*16 =9.\n\nWait if we subtract small number from the big one.\n\nWait perhaps the key is working with the remainder when divided by GCD?\n\nWait the first player to reduce it such that the opponent is left with a pair where they can force a win.\n\nAlternatively, the starting position 320 and500. Since GCD is20, and both starting numbers are multiples of 20.\n\nThe key here is to realize the starting player can win by removing multiples.\n\nPerhaps the outcome is determined by whether the starting number is a multiple of GCD and the ratio is not 1.\n\nWait the original numbers are 320 and500, with GCD 20, so scaling to16 and25.\n\nIf the second player mirrors or whatever... since GCD is 20, may