dition is if you make one number zero after a player\'s move. So if after the subtraction, either number is zero, the player who did that wins.\n\nIf the pair becomes (0, x), then the current player has won because x is non-zero but? Wait, plz check the rules.\n\nWait, when you do the subtraction and make a number zero, you win. Let me see.\n\nLet me take the first case:\n\nSt几年前: starting pair, both 15.\n\nStan subtract k *15 from the other 15 with k positive integer, so k must be 1? Because it would make it 0, so numbers become 0 and 15.\n\nSince subtracting 1*15 would make one of the numbers zero: 15 - 15 =0, making the pair (0, 15). Since one of the numbers is zero, who then wins?\n\nWhich player would result in making a zero? It seems that the player who causes this would win. So if Stan can make a zero, then he wins. But if both play optimally.\n\nWait: Let me lay this out step by step. Let me model it.\n\nStarting state: (15, 15)\n\nStan moves first. He subtracts 1 time 15 from the second from the first. Wait, wait both numbers are equal, so he can subtract 1* first number from the second (if they are reversed). Wait, the player can subtract any positive multiple of one integer from the other.\n\nSo on the move, he can subtract k*number 1 (which is 15) from number 2 (also 15). So:\n\nOption 1: subtract 1*15 from 15: resulting (15 -1*15, 15)= (0,15). Then, the pair is (0,15). Since one of them is zero, which would make Stan the winner because he made it.\n\nWait, but wait, if subtraction results in zero, the next number is non-zero: winner is who made it happen? Wait, according to the problem, "the player who makes one of the numbers zero wins." So when one becomes zero on a player\'s move, they win.\n\nSo if Stan subtracts 1*15 from 15, making one zero and then the next state has (0, 15), meaning Stan has already achieved a condition where a number becomes zero, so Stan wins. But is that necessarily so?\n\nWait, let me confirm the exact rule: Each turn, "subt