ilarly, subtract m*16 from 11: but m would have to satisfy m*16 <=11, m=0 only? Which gives (11,16), same position but we probably ignore same player not changing? Not because the player must move.\n\nWait, the rule says subtract "any positive multiple": so subtracting 0 wouldn\'t change the number but m is positive, so subtraction is non-zero and multiple at least 1.\n\nTherefore from 16 subtract >=1 *11, so only m=1: going to 5, so pair becomes (11,5).\n\nAnother option is subtract multiples of 16:\n\nSubtract m*16 – since 16 from 11 is negative, which is invalid as the result must non-negative. So only (m via 11*). So only one option moving next: (11,5).\n\nAlternatively, maybe we consider swapping:\n\nSince b >a, swap if needed, swap (5,11)? But let me think in terms of subtracting.\n\nSo from (11,16), the first possible next move is landing at (5, 11). Wait, wait:\n\nWait, wait, if you subtract a multiple of 1 from the 16.\n\nWait no. In each turn, you can subtract any positive multiple of one of the numbers from the other.\n\nSo it\'s either:\n\nFrom pair (a,b), you can subtract k*a from b, resulting in b - k*a, or subtract k*b from a, but if that gives non-negative number.\n\nBut since a < b here (11 < 16), let\'s examine only the possible moves as  subtracting multiple of 11 from 16 or multiple multiples.\n\nLet me consider the allowed moves:\n\nCase 1: subtract multiple of 11 from 16.\n\nPossible k:  floor(16/11)= once, so k=1: 16-11*1=5, leading to (11, 5).\n\nk=0 leads to (11,16).\n\nBut can\'t stay same unless k=0 isn\'t legal.\n\nTherefore the next positions are (11, 5).\n\nSimilarly, Case 2: subtract multiple of 16 from 11: since 16>11, can\'t subtract 16 even once, as it would lead to negative number, which isn\'t allowed. So only valid move is moving from b to (a, b - a).\n\nWait wait, hold on, maybe it\'s using the Euclidean algorithm idea where the possible next moves are computing (b - k*a), b >a:\n\nSo first pair is (11,16), subtract k*11:\n\nCal